            <font size=3D"3" face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
            </font><font size=3D"3" face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><=
b>The Historians=20
            amongst you will really appreciate this Greek Philosophical Tes=
t<br>
            </b><br>
            Keep this in mind the next time you are about to repeat a rumou=
r or=20
            spread gossip.<br>
            <br>
            In ancient Greece (469 - 399 BC), Socrates was widely lauded fo=
r his=20
            wisdom.<br>
            <br>
            One day an acquaintance ran up to him excitedly and said, &quot=
;Socrates,=20
            do you know what I just heard about Diogenes?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;Wait a moment,&quot; Socrates replied, &quot;Before you t=
ell=20
            me I'd like you to pass a little test. It's called the Triple F=
ilter=20
            Test.&quot;<br>
            <br>
            'Triple filter?&quot; asked the acquaintance.<br>
            <br>
            &quot;That's right,&quot; Socrates continued, &quot;Before you =
talk=20
            to me about Diogenes let's take a moment to filter what you're =
going=20
            to say. The first filter is Truth. Have you made absolutely sur=
e that=20
            what you are about to tell me is true?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;No,&quot; the man said, &quot;Actually I just heard about=
 it.&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;All right,&quot; said Socrates, &quot;So you don't really=
 know=20
            if it's true or not. Now let's try the second filter, the filte=
r of=20
            Goodness. Is what you are about to tell me about Diogenes somet=
hing=20
            good?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;No, on the contrary...&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;So,&quot; Socrates continued, &quot;You want to tell me s=
omething=20
            about Diogenes that may be bad, even though you're not certain =
it's=20
            true?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            The man shrugged, a little embarrassed. Socrates continued, &qu=
ot;You=20
            may still pass the test though, because there is a third filter=
, the=20
            filter of Usefulness. Is what you want to tell me about Diogene=
s going=20
            to be useful to me?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;No, not really.&quot;<br>
            <br>
            &quot;Well,&quot; concluded Socrates, &quot;If what you want to=
 tell=20
            me is neither True nor Good nor even Useful, why tell it to me =
or=20
            anyone at all?&quot;<br>
            <br>
            The man was bewildered and ashamed. This is an example of why S=
ocrates=20
            was a great philosopher and held in such high esteem.<br>
            <br>
            It also explains why Socrates never found out that Diogenes was=
 shagging=20
            his wife.</font><br> <br> <font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-=
serif"><br>
